2026-04-21 01:28:45 | INFO     | DiagnosticAssistantLLM | OUTPUT: suggestion_type='hypothesis' action_type=None action_target=None action_description=None suspected_components=['Control Module 6'] hypothesis_explanation='Control Module 6’s indicator LED and its series resistor are physically missing. In this design the LED–resistor branch is wired directly between the module’s 12 V and 0 V lines. If that branch was implemented as part of the current path (e.g., the LED/resistor pads are in series or otherwise required to complete copper continuity), then removing both components leaves an open circuit between the incoming and outgoing terminals of Control Module 6. Since the chain is strictly series from PSU through control modules 1–8 to the load, this single open in Module 6 will interrupt current to all downstream modules: the subsequent control-module LEDs and the load (lamp and its indicator) all remain off, while the PSU LED still lights because it is only in parallel with the battery. Therefore the most likely root cause of the observed symptoms (PSU LED on, all control-module LEDs absent, load lamp off) is an internal open circuit in Control Module 6 caused by the missing LED/resistor assembly. Replacing or repairing Control Module 6 should restore continuity and allow the downstream indicators and lamp to operate when the switches are on.'
